Disproportionate obligations surrounding family and children are considered to be the most important factor that limits women from entering the labour market, while structural problems are perceived as difficulties that simply lie in how things are organised, or something that can be regulated. Women and men, however, opted for rather different conceptualisations of what these problems were. While women tended to focus on child care, health care and earnings, men focussed much more on taxation issues and lack of a support network. Men were also driven in their views by more ideological reasons.
The discussion can be summarised by one respondent, Alla, who says that while not possible, there is “no need and no
wish for such a dramatic solution as leaving Ukraine. Everything is
adjustable. My younger men colleagues say – with a smile – that part of it is a utopia and they are going to marry abroad in future, but I have an opposite view. A better life doesn’t follow you to the country, instead you
will have the opposite, you simply will live abroad, unhappily.
It is necessary to move forward somehow – and despite the economic
difficulties – that is the way. But you should change job and realise you
need change. And should pay less for domestic help.” (Alla, 39 years old, 3 children) Conclusions As shown by the responses of Ukrainian women to various issues relating to their paid employment, women in Ukraine suffer a great
